The paper focuses on studying the behaviors of traffic participants while crossing, which involves analyzing non-verbal communication cues and responses. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses a dataset of pedestrian behaviors, which could fall under the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The analysis of the data also involves identifying factors such as time to collision and driver's reaction, which could be related to Robotics (cs.RO) and Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories, respectively. Finally, the paper deals with the safety and security aspects of crossing, which could be relevant to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category.
